properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 15 cm is expected. A frontal system pushing across the BC Interior is spreading snow to Pine Pass. The light snow falling this morning will become occasionally heavy this afternoon and evening before the snow tapers off after midnight. Total snowfall accumulations of 10 to 15 cm are expected from this afternoon through midnight. ### Weather in the mountains can change suddenly resulting in hazardous driving conditions. Road conditions are available at www.drivebc.ca. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow Squall Watch upgraded from Winter Weather Travel Advisory. A brief but intense snow squall band associated with a cold front is expected to cross portions of far northern Ontario today. This band will extend from roughly Sachigo Lake towards Sandy Lake by late morning and will race eastward to reach the Webequie region by late afternoon or early evening. Northwest winds gusting to 70 km/h combined with heavy snow during the passage of the front will likely result in a brief period of very poor visibility and whiteout conditions. A general snowfall accumulation of 4 to 8 cm is possible. ### Visibility may be significantly and suddenly reduced to near zero. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A period of very cold wind chills is expected. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Risks are greater for young children, older adults, people with chronic illnesses, people working or exercising outdoors, and those without proper shelter. Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia. For more information on cold and your health, visit Manitoba Health at https://www.gov.mb.ca/health/publichealth/environmentalhealth/cold.html or call Health Links - Info Santé at 204-788-8200 or toll-free at 1-888-315-9257. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

properties.Summary:

Extreme wind chill values of -45 or colder are expected to develop by late this afternoon and persist through the night. Temperatures will moderate Saturday as another system moves in from the west. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Risks are greater for young children, older adults, people with chronic illnesses, people working or exercising outdoors, and those without proper shelter. Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia. Description: Winter Weather Travel Advisory in effect for today. A narrow but intense snow squall band, associated with the passage of a cold front, will move across northern Ontario today. This linear snow squall band will extend from Sachigo Lake to Red Lake late this morning and is expected to move eastward throughout the day reaching Webequie and Savant Lake by late afternoon. A snowfall accumulation of 4 to 8 cm is possible with this snow squall. Strong winds with gusts up to 60 km/h are also possible with the passage of the cold front today. These winds are expected to ease Friday evening. Under the snow squall bands, visibilities will be significantly reduced due to the heavy snow combined with blowing snow, and snow will accumulate quickly. Travel is expected to be hazardous due to the reduced visibility. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. Blizzard developing later this morning and ending early Saturday. An intensifying low pressure system over Hudson Bay will bring strengthening northwesterly winds and blowing snow to the Kivalliq coast today. Winds gusting to 70 km/h are expected by late this morning accompanied by deterioration to blizzard. The blizzard will continue into the night before easing Saturday morning. In addition, temperatures will continue to fall today, and extreme wind chill values near -55 will settle into the area tonight into early Saturday. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A vigorous frontal system moving onto the South Coast this morning is spreading strong winds and heavy rain to the region. Over central sections of East Vancouver Island near Qualicum Beach, rain will become heavy this morning and approximately 50 mm of rainfall is forecast by late this afternoon, when the front passes through and the rain tapers off. ### Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. Blizzard beginning Friday morning and ending in the evening. A low pressure tracking across the northern Prairies continues to give snow to the Churchill area, with totals expected to reach 10 centimetres. On Friday morning, strong northerly winds of 60 gusting 80 km/h will rapidly develop as the system moves into Hudson Bay. As a result of the snow and wind, blizzard conditions will develop by mid morning Friday and will last until the winds ease Friday evening. In addition, temperatures are forecast to fall throughout the day bringing near extreme wind chill values in the -45 to -50 range by Friday afternoon into the night. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 6 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls are expected to develop. Under the snow squall bands, visibilities will be significantly reduced due to the heavy snow, and snow will quickly accumulate. A cold front moving across northern Ontario today, will bring southerly winds over lake Superior that may generate lake effect snow squalls. These snow squalls are expected to develop late this afternoon or this evening in an area stretching from Marathon east to Wawa and south to Agawa. Heavy bursts of snow and significantly reduced visibilities at times can be expected late this afternoon and tonight. Travel along Highway 17 during this time may be hazardous. A total snowfall accumulation of 10 to 15 cm is possible by Saturday morning. Areas closer the lake shore where the temperature is slightly above the freezing mark may accumulate less snow than areas further inland. The snow squalls will begin to weaken near midnight for Marathon and Wawa and by Saturday morning for Agawa. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
Expires: 2020-12-19T02:03:16-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2020-12-18T10:03:16-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.1848912301.2020
Area: Marathon - Schreiber, White River - Dubreuilville, Wawa - Pukaskwa Park, Agawa - Lake Superior Park

properties.Title: Freezing Drizzle Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: An extended period of freezing drizzle is expected. Locations: northeastern Newfoundland. Time span: today, tonight, and Saturday. Remarks: Some areas, especially along the coast, will likely see a changeover to drizzle or flurries today as temperatures rise just above zero. Precipitation for all areas is forecast to change back to a mix of freezing drizzle and flurries tonight and persist through much of Saturday. Conditions are expected to improve Saturday afternoon into Saturday night as the persistent northeasterly flow weakens. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots will become icy, slippery and hazardous. Freezing drizzle advisories are issued when drizzle falling in sub-zero temperatures is expected to freeze on contact, and over time create icy surfaces. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard possible Saturday. A strong low pressure system will make its way through Hudson Bay toward southern Baffin Island on Friday. Heavy snow is expected to begin late Friday or early Saturday along with rapidly intensifying easterly winds. Current indications are for up to 10 cm of fresh snow accompanied at times with winds gusting to 80 km/h. At minimum, visibility reductions in blowing snow are expected for much of Saturday. Blizzard conditions will also be possible should the system continue on its current forecast track or intensify further. Conditions will improve late Saturday as the system moves off into Foxe Basin. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Blowing Snow Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Poor visibility due to blowing snow is expected this afternoon and evening. Heavy snow and strong westerly winds with gusts of 70 to 80 km/h will affect the region beginning late this afternoon as an intense cold front moves east across northern Ontario today and tonight. The heavy snow and strong winds occurring together will result in blowing snow that will significantly reduce visibilities late this afternoon and this evening. As the cold front moves east, the heavy snow will taper to flurries late in the evening, however the winds will remain strong and could continue to whip up the freshly fallen snow. Conditions are expected to improve early Saturday morning as the winds diminish. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blowing snow advisories are issued when winds are expected to create blowing snow giving poor visibility to 800 metres or less for at least 3 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
